python with a problem


This fairly large python (sorry we never measured it) had recently eaten one of my goat weaners as evidenced by the stretched skin and spaced scales of its mid-section. On leaving the scene it had headed off through a veldspan fence the mesh at the base being about 15 x 12cm and this is where we found it next morning, stuck solid, needless to say it was a little upset. I think the open mouth and visible teeth was more from pain and fear than from aggression though.

There is little doubt about the identification, the size, the reticulate markings, the small smooth scales and all those teeth in an elongated triangular head with a spear-shaped brown patch on top and the broad cream coloured stripe over each eye are unmistakable.

Officers from our Dept of Wildlife were summoned and after they secured the biting end we were able to cut open the fence and free the poor thing. The python was taken away and relocated, It regurgitated its meal during this translocation which was a bit of a waste of a goat but the python appeared to have suffered no permanent damage from the ordeal

Python^s Fatal Error


Strange story: A friend was at a private farm. He entered a bower and grabbed a gum pole, only to leap away when he discover it was a python hanging vertically, its head in hole in the tree above.
Turned out the snake was dead, strangled by its own weight, when they pulled it out of the tree it had a squirrel in its mouth.
My guess is that while attacking the squirrel it lost its purchase on the tree or the thatched roof it approached from and fell.

I think I have a frog in my throat - Montagu WCape


The Slangverklikkers alerted me to the presence of this cobra (otherwise I would never have seen it). It had its head stuck down a hole for ages, and I thought it may have run out of solar power because it was cold and drizzling at the time (the weather not the cobra).

About 45 mins after first seeing it, it pulled up its head with a massive frog in its jaws. I have never seen such a big frog here! Could the frog have bloated with the effects of the venom? Or perhaps it just looks enormous because it is being squashed to fit in the cobra's mouth...? Do we get bullfrogs in the karoo?

The pics are rubbish coz I took them through a window and did not want to go any closer for fear that the snake would regurgitate its meal, which is just a waste. The day was so cold, that I thought the snake would be more likely to regurgitate when it was already thermodynamically compromised.

It took about 20 mins for the frog to go down. And after some rather icky looking gagging, the cobra gently wandered off to look for further munchies.

Hogmanay Feast


The rope!
skip this: go to the interaction first and come here last ...
.
part #3 in which we with our drams watch the drama in the Hogmanay Pool.
.
With crab out of the way and in deep water the frog kept the pressure on and swam strongly, so that the snake could not coil around it. The snake soon gave up trying and went long and rigid until its tail touched the bank. It hooked this around a sedge and reeled in the frog, dragging it onto land, whereupon it threw its coils around the frog and all went still, apart from an occasional twitch from the frog, or tightening of the snakes coils, and Sirius and Jupiter appearing in the gloaming. After dark we retired to set up camp, and about an hour later on return the snake had just finished swallowing the frog. On next inspection 10 minutes later there was no trace of anyone.
.

Roll on 2015 ...

good deed, unexpected complication


heading home, quiet rural road, snake dashes into road, bakkie from the opposite direction is closer and intent on running said snake down but my presence intervenes especially as I'm able to stop between the hunters and their intended prey which has reversed direction in the confusion. Bakkie occupants leap out and arming themselves with sticks and rocks approach (no threat to me they just want the snake which is behind me somewhere). Consternation; the snake has not been seen to escape but it has disappeared, some minutes later discovered hiding behind the rear light fitting of my truck - it had obviously headed for the nearest cover, but it was well wedged in and pretty inaccessible. The would-be killers, ignoring my pleas to let it live tried poking and cajoling the snake out (a big Boomslang by the way) which only resulted in upsetting the creature which then proceeded to hiss and squeeze in more tightly. Time to go I thought so saying farewell to the disappointed hunters I drove off a km down the road, pulled over and wondered what to do next - I have enough pets, I didn't really need a +/-1.2m Boomslang in my yard. The branch under the truck was a vain attempt to encourage snake to depart, 45 mins no progress except the tail had relaxed a little and a loop was hanging down; sun setting; salvation arrived in the form of a local contract, and acquaintance, who was passing; his mate confidently found a long stout stick and set about carefully loosening a loop of snake, the first attempt brought out 50 cm of tail which was rapidly withdrawn but made another thicker loop available, once the snake decided to flee the security of the truck it MOVED, so even though the I had the camera ready I nearly missed getting a shot. Happy ending.

The snake had to be a Boomslang although I did not get to see the head; at 1m plus and as thick as my wrist, it was bright green changing to yellow under the belly, although the tail end was all green, scales keeled dorsally, the location is inland and around 1000m (3000ft) .a.s.l.

Some white meat please, preferably from the neck


Another series of fascinating shots kind courtesy of Mary McKenzie.

Mary says: "Our Sunday (Umdoni) Forest Walk: I think whatever was eating him heard us, dropped it and ran. Hopefully to return when all quiet to complete the meal…."

Of the predator I can only speculate Mongoose of some kind. At least 3 species are known to occur there: Banded, Water (Marsh) and Slender. Ratel aren't forest dwellers and have never been seen there. Genet would surely have carried it off. It wasn't a particularly large snake - under half a metre remained. The pictures were shot at 7:59 am.

description: Eggy

Snakie Om-nom-nom


A Karoo Prinia chattering somewhere in a bush next to the path ahead of me, drew my attention when I noticed vigorous shaking of vegetation close to the ground, which I took to be the related to the Prinia at first. Only when I took a closer look with my binoculars, did I spot the distressed Agama, rigid and slowly opening and closing its mouth - and then it became clear that the cause of the apparent distress was the grip of the snake across the chest area just behind the front legs.
The snake then deliberately maneuvered its mouth sideways towards the head of the Agama, and after about four minutes after first spotting it, it had aligned the Agama's head to be pointing straight into its mouth for the swallowing process to begin.
The snake then suddenly moved forward about eight inches, and seemed to use the rock to stabilise the Agama to get the head into its mouth, then it swung around again locating the its prey alongside its body for some more maneuvering, before moving out of sight into the vegetation behind the rock. Dennis did get a glimpse of the snake again, with just the tip of the tail of the Agama still visible, about 10 to 15 minutes after first observation.
Lesson to be learnt - listen to the birds - they often advertise the presence of predators.

Lesson to be learnt - listen to the birds - they often advertise the presence of predators.

Gif of puffy walking, because it is an amazing sight and people don't believe you that they move like this unless they've seen it themselves.

Genie Retief (who kindly provided the pics) wrote: "This spotted bush snake fell, with the gecko, from the balcony. Then he dragged it behind a pot plant. Ants started to climb on both of them so he moved again. He lost the gecko, who tried to run away! Caught it again, then a skink came closer and bit the snake. He whipped his tail away from the skink then pushed his tail and body backwards up the wall, away from the ants and the skink... Then started swallowing the gecko."
